metadata.name: Inertia #834
metadata.description:
This project will be reserved and free for 48 hours, for all the holders of any of my projects!

The amount of reserves for each user will be equal to the amount of all the token held at 13:00 CEST [UTC+2] (May 23)
(example: user holds 3 "Figment" and 2 "ACCUMULATOR", will be able to mint "Inertia" 5 times)

48h from now I will update the reserves list and burn the remaining tokens

WARINING: The reserves will expire 48h after the drop! And a price for the unlocked mintables will be set (unreserved mints will not be free).

---

"Inertia is a property of matter by which it continues in its existing state of rest or uniform motion in a straight line, unless that state is changed by an external force."

Particles are blasted from 2 to 4 sides of the canvas, each particle has its own mass and it has to traverse a friction-field, once it loses its momentum completely it stops and leaves a trace, adding or subtracting light from the canvas.

The friction-field has 18 possible mutation kinds.
Mutations are high-friction zones of various shapes.

Made just with JS on a canvas
right-click to save

metadata.name: Constellations #23
metadata.description:
We look at things that are seemingly random and can't help but form relationships between them. For centuries people of many different nations and cultures have looked up to the skies and perceived patterns, objects, mythical creatures from scattered stars.

This work, initially titled 'Chaos', began as a study for my project 'Gestalt' to explore the idea of working with a foundation of hidden random points and connecting points with curves in interesting ways. Almost by accident I discovered a technique which ended up creating outputs resembling scenes from some otherworldly cosmos. While it produced some visually interesting outputs, they didn't quite fit the direction for 'Gestalt' and only a portion of the algorithm was used. 

The study was recently revisited and further refined to explore something different to 'Gestalt' (yet would nod to it), blur the lines between abstraction and figuration, and lean into the atmospheric moodiness of that once accidental output. 'Constellations' plays with the concept of interconnectivity, the meeting and interacting of hidden elements, and the emergence of patterns and interpretations from chance encounters (or kismet).

---

Released for VerticalCrypto Art invites | LONDON 2022.

---

Controls:
• 'R' reassembles the piece
• 'B' toggles the frame

Note: Some mints may take time to fully render in live mode.

Made in p5js

metadata.name: Landscapes out of my mind #86
metadata.description:
In this work, the third in the series of landscapes, I tried to achieve greater realism without abandoning those elements, also characteristic of the other works, which lead out of reality such as the shapes of the ground and trees and the choice of palettes.

Lands and Clouds are rendered using a mix of simplex noise and FBM (Fractional Brownian Motion), trees are generated with space colonization algorithm an placed using Poisson Disk Sampling distribution. The distribution density is driven by the land heightmap.


Developed with three.js using WebGLRenderer.
Rendering is faster with chrome browser.


[s] to save a png at 2048x1536, 1536x2048, 2048x2048 (4/3, 3/4, 4/4 aspect ratio)
[d] to save a png at 4096x3072, 3072x4096, 4096x4096 (4/3, 3/4, 4/4 aspect ratio)


Features:
"Palette": 14 colormaps
"Aspect Ratio": 4/3, 3/4, 4/4
"View Point":  Far, Medium, Near, Above
"Sky Type": FBM, Gradient1, Gradient2
"Sky Color": LightSkyBlue, Gray, Blue [10% probability]

metadata.name: Diamond Fractal Fire #89
metadata.description:
Diamond Fractal Fire interposes recursively generated poetry with similarly recursive fractal imagery. Each text (unique for each mint, but always 20 sentences in length) is generated by a custom context-free grammar algorithm, fed with lists of words selected by the creator. The fractal pattern in each edition is a variation on a Koch snowflake fractal, one of the earliest fractals described by mathematicians. These fractals grow over time at varying rates, and pulse with varying color ranges using Perlin noise, eventually filling the screen.


Push `h` to save high resolution PNG and JPG images of the complete fractal pattern (takes a moment to process)
Push `s` to save PNG and JPG images of the current browser view (with current browser window dimensions and resolution)
Push `v` to begin recording canvas as a video (with current browser window dimensions), then push `v` again to save the video
Push `f` to toggle fullscreen mode
Push `p` to toggle zoom pause
Push `r` to toggle zoom reverse
Push `c` to toggle color shift pause
Push `l` to toggle low resolution mode (improves framerate)


The animation is somewhat computationally expensive, and so it runs best on contemporary laptop and desktop computers. Mobile devices and older computers may experience low frame rates. Captured video quality may vary depending on compute and browser limitations. The animation is responsive (it will adapt to any screen or window size), and resizing your browser window also will restart the animation.

Color floors and variances represent ranges for Hue using a Hue/Saturation/Brightness (HSB) color model. Velocities represent (subtle) zoom speed differences. Noise increment and start values affect the rate and variation of color shifts.

In addition to the author's code, Diamond Fractal Fire relies on the p5.js library.

metadata.name: The seed :: issue 1 #42
metadata.description:
*the seed* is an experimental project, meaning that we give ourselves permission to test the waters and see where the current takes us. *the seed* is also a zine, which suggests something both unpretentious and grassroots — it's most definitely a labor of love!

The first issue is on the minimalist side, with a total of 19 pages nonetheless! We avoided big blocks of text and leaned into finding creative solutions to allow the artists to express themselves without having to produce new work. We also elected not to systematically showcase an artist's latest project as a way of jumping off the cultural treadmill which has conditioned us to focus almost exclusively on "what's new" and "what's next". As a result, *the seed*, which we envisage as a quarterly publication, will hopefully convey a certain quality of timelessness.

This issue is a collective invitation to catch our breath and celebrate the beauty that has been brought forth by a diverse group of amazing artists from all over the world: Lammetje, Liam Egan, Ciput, Elsif & Clint Fulkerson. Instead of asking the typical interview questions, we invited each artist to introduce themselves using a text based recording device which allows the reader to witness the workings of the artist's mind. The result feels both lighthearted and intimate.

The edition size is 128 and statistically one in five coverpages will be an animated collage created using the artwork of one of our five artists. No two coverpages are alike as the seed differs for each collage. This might be less apparent if the project is only examined through thumbnails. Please take the time to explore all of the interactive features of *the seed* on full screen.

*the seed* was made with C++ and OpenGL and converted to the web via Emscripten.

Thank you for reading this metadata and for coming on this journey with us!

metadata.name: Forest Sunrise #32
metadata.description:
A forest at sunrise can be a magical place. Rays from the sun can stream through the trees and reveal interesting patterns in the air and on the forest floor. Mist can lend an atmosphere of mystery.

In this 100% generative work I wanted to depict this type of scene. It's also my first animated art. I wanted to experiment with slow subtle animation and I think the birds and mist bring the work to life.

Primary Features:
Birds : Low, Medium, High
Sky : Red, Blue (with variations)
Fog Level : Low, Medium, High, Very High
Fog Direction : Right, Left

metadata.name: Starmap - AI Study I #230
metadata.description:
Starmap brings you to different sectors of the generative art galaxy. A first of its kind generative art experiment using a Text2Code workflow, which involves writing text prompts that get translated into javascript code. This project was created with English words and human imagination, but the programming of the piece is all AI.

The code for this project was written entirely by AI using GPT-3. None of the code was altered or created by a human aside from changing some Math.random() with fxrand().

Text2Code study #1 /// Project CoDexter by @BrainArtLabs
